    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that makes sense. i also heard there's a difference between caramelization and the maillard reaction? i always get them mixed up since they both result in browning/sweetness. could u clarify the main distinction between the two?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly. Caramelization is the chemical process by which sugar breaks down and forms new compounds, resulting in a rich, brown color and sweet flavor. This process occurs at higher temperatures, usually above 160°C (320°F), and does not require the presence of amino acids. In contrast, the Maillard reaction involves amino acids and reducing sugars, resulting in a complex mixture of molecules that contribute to the savory flavor of browned foods. It's important not to conflate the two, as they are distinct processes that occur under different conditions and contribute different flavors to foods.",
      "source": "target",
